english:
  title: A Memorial Offering to Master Wonmyo, the National Preceptor
  author: Seok Cheonin
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I reflect upon the ancient Awakened Sage, who suddenly illuminated the suffering realm and comprehended the profound way within the circle, gazing upon all things without distinction. He bent low to guide the weak and destitute, transcending the three realms of existence. Entering the supreme nature and the realm of true suchness, he divided the teaching into partial and complete according to the capacity of each being—sharp or dull. Thus the paths of the goat and deer diverged, and the treasure-place remained yet distant. Each clung to their own position, none achieving unity. Only upon Vulture Peak did he fulfill his original vow, revealing the wondrous meaning of the lotus, showing that the nine realms and three vehicles are but one without duality. Thus the great matter of cause and effect reached its sublime perfection—appearing like the udumbara flower, which blooms but once in ages.

    Since the Buddha's passing, the sage Nagarjuna arose, opening the gate of contemplation and first proclaiming it in India. When the Wise Master came, he emerged brilliantly in the latter age—endowed by past karma with the heaven-bestowed wonder of enlightenment. His words flowed like the river in eloquent torrents, becoming exemplars for a thousand ages. But nine generations hence, subtle teachings became rare to hear. Though later students sought and aspired, the path forward lay sealed. The clouds gathered over Yicheon's legacy, dust dimmed the mirror of dharma. The orthodox lineage of Tiantai barely persisted as a single thread. When the dharma became distorted and corrupted, how could one not grieve? Alas! Yet the way did not perish. Heaven sent forth a master—our noble teacher, majestic and resolute. In youth, fallen into the world yet chosen among scholars; matured, he yearned for the way and departed for the mountains. Wandering like clouds through famous peaks, he settled in Tana. Students aspired to him, gathering like rice and hemp from all directions. Finding the mountain hermitage too cramped, he established Gold Garden by the sea and gently guided his monastic community. Following the ancient practice of half-walking, half-sitting, he led them through the ten stages and purified their minds with the three contemplations, dwelling deep in samadhi, refining day by day. For fifty years he wore the single robe upon the blue mountains, his standing utterly without peer.

    Alas! Time did not favor us. Though voices multiplied with doubt, he remained unstained and pure as refined gold and genuine jade. Thus the world revered him, and his dharma-medicine flowed without measure, like turbid wine becoming clear. Reflecting on myself, the insignificant one, I abandoned my parents in the north and sought the way in the south, where needle and metal came together. Your compassionate guidance became my second birth, surpassing even parents. Wishing to repay a ten-thousandth of this kindness, I saw no other means. I only hoped to serve for a hundred years, offering sustenance at proper times, never failing in medicine, dwelling in ease, sitting in stillness—this was my sole aspiration.

    Yet how could a single morning bring such sudden change? The master, knowing his time in advance as autumn's close, prepared his traveling clothes and composed his form, gently resolving my lingering doubts. Where now do you wander, venerable one? Surely to the jeweled trees by the golden western heaven, there to play in paradise. From the master's perspective, all is extinction and inaction; going and staying flow naturally—what doubt remains, what thought disturbs? But from my vantage, birth and death stand opposed. My grief pierces deepest, my heart cannot hold firm. Day after day I can only sigh heavily.

    Alas! The wind that shakes the tree does not cease, the dew upon the grass dries easily. Heaven has not preserved you for me. Upon whom shall I now depend? Wind and mist grow desolate, the world's aspect transforms. Dragons rise and phoenixes depart; wells dry and forests wither. What is living, what is death? We cannot know. Is this dream or waking? It cannot be pursued. The sincerity I hold finds nowhere to extend itself. Yet with pure offerings made humbly here, if my steadfast faith proves sincere, surely spiritual response must come. May you turn your celestial chariot and savor this humble memorial.
  footnotes:
    - 'Vulture Peak (靈山): The mountain where the Buddha preached the Lotus Sutra, a central location in Mahayana Buddhism.'
    - The udumbara flower blooms only once every three thousand years, symbolizing the rare appearance of enlightenment.
    - 'Nagarjuna (龍樹): Foundational figure in Mahayana Buddhism, credited with establishing key interpretive traditions.'
    - 'The Wise Master (智者): Refers to Zhiyi, founder of the Tiantai school of Buddhism.'
    - 'Gold Garden (金園): The monastery where the master taught, located by the sea.'
    - 'The ten stages and three contemplations: Technical Buddhist meditative practices central to Tiantai practice.'
    - The rhetorical contrast between the master's perspective (seeing all as empty, non-dual) and the author's perspective (experiencing the grief of death) expresses a central tension in Buddhist philosophy between ultimate and conventional truth.
